From 479ab34354a6e328995b722d6b255cb710b53442 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: uml-veristat build <uml-veristat@build>
Date: Wed, 22 Apr 2026 00:15:29 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 7/7] libbpf: relo_core: keep first TYPE_ID_TARGET candidate on
 duplicate types

On UML, vmlinux BTF can contain structurally-equivalent duplicate types
because glibc headers are included alongside kernel headers during the
build.  For example, struct sockaddr_un appears twice with different BTF
IDs.

When bpf_core_calc_field_relos() encounters two matching candidates for
a BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET relocation, both succeed but with different
new_val (the kernel BTF type ID).  The existing ambiguity check treats
this as a fatal error and returns -EINVAL.

For BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET specifically, new_val is the BTF type ID of
the target type.  When two candidates are structurally equivalent
duplicates (same name, same layout -- they both passed bpf_core_spec_match),
the difference in new_val is purely an artifact of the duplicate type
registration.  It is safe to keep the first (lower) BTF ID, which
corresponds to the canonical kernel definition.

This mirrors the approach taken in btf_relocate.c for the same class of
duplicates.

Fixes: BPF CO-RE relocation failures on UML for programs using
bpf_core_cast() or other TYPE_ID_TARGET relocations against types that
appear as duplicates in vmlinux BTF (e.g. getsockname_unix_prog.bpf.o,
netif_receive_skb.bpf.o).

Signed-off-by: BPF UML CI <bpf-uml-ci@example.com>
---
 tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c | 17 +++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 17 insertions(+)

diff --git a/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c b/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
index 0ccc8f548..189a97f29 100644
--- a/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
+++ b/tools/lib/bpf/relo_core.c
@@ -1385,6 +1385,23 @@ int bpf_core_calc_relo_insn(const char *prog_name,
 			return -EINVAL;
 		} else if (cand_res.poison != targ_res->poison ||
 			   cand_res.new_val != targ_res->new_val) {
+			/* For BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET, new_val is the kernel BTF
+			 * type ID of the candidate.  On UML, vmlinux BTF can
+			 * contain structurally-equivalent duplicate types (e.g.
+			 * struct sockaddr_un appears twice because glibc headers
+			 * are included alongside kernel headers during the build).
+			 * Both candidates match and succeed, but with different
+			 * BTF IDs.  Keep the first (lower) ID -- it is the
+			 * canonical kernel definition -- and skip the duplicate.
+			 */
+			if (relo->kind == BPF_CORE_TYPE_ID_TARGET &&
+			    !cand_res.poison && !targ_res->poison) {
+				pr_debug("prog '%s': relo #%d: TYPE_ID_TARGET ambiguity: keeping first candidate (id %llu), skipping duplicate (id %llu)\n",
+					 prog_name, relo_idx,
+					 (unsigned long long)targ_res->new_val,
+					 (unsigned long long)cand_res.new_val);
+				continue;
+			}
 			/* all candidates should result in the same relocation
 			 * decision and value, otherwise it's dangerous to
 			 * proceed due to ambiguity
-- 
